SIMPLE: methodist
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Methodist
<hw>Meth"o*dist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧thodiste</ets>. See <er>Method</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>One who observes method.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of an ancient school of physicians who rejected
observation and founded their practice on reasoning and theory.</def>
<rj><au>Sir W. Hamilton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>One of a sect of Christians, the
outgrowth of a small association called the ⟦ldquo⟧Holy Club,⟦rdquo⟧
formed at Oxford University, <sc>a. d.</sc> 1729, of which the most
conspicuous members were <person>John Wesley</person> and his brother
<person>Charles Wesley</person>; -- originally so called from the
methodical strictness of members of the club in all religious
duties.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A person of strict piety; one who lives in the exact
observance of religious duties; -- sometimes so called in contempt or
ridicule.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodist</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Methodist
<hw>Meth"o*dist</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining to the sect of
Methodists; <as>as, <ex>Methodist</ex> hymns; a <ex>Methodist</ex>
elder.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Methodistical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Methodistic</ent>⟦br⟧
